<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I257d4190630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>B.</label.designator><headtext>Competency</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05bc682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:7.</label.designator><headtext>General rule of competency</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In Georgia, every person is presumed competent to be a witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7655aff074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Competency is defined as <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/><?page no="11"?>“the presence of those characteristics, or the absence of those disabilities, which render a witness legally fit and qualified to give testimony in a court of justice.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7655d70074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] A party should enter competency objections prior to the witness&apos; testimony.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7655d70174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Preliminary questions concerning the qualification of a person to be a witness, the existence of a privilege, or the admissibility of evidence shall be determined by the court.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7655fe1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The court does not need to evaluate witness competency absent a competency objection.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7655fe1174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] If the court does conduct a competency examination, it may choose whether to do it in the presence or outside the presence of the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7656252074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] Any evidence the court considers in a competency hearing may be used by the jury to evaluate witness credibility if the witness testifies.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76564c3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] The court may[<footnote.reference refid="I76564c3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] but is not required to allow counsel to question a witness in a competency examination.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76564c3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] A defendant is not entitled to attend the hearing.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1987076784" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I9178f90274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Kentucky v. Stincer</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7656734074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] the U.S. Supreme Court held that the trial court did not violate defendant&apos;s constitutional due process and confrontation rights when it excluded him from competency hearings on two child witnesses.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In a competency examination, the court may examine someone other than the witness in question.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76569a5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The court may use its discretion to allow the jury to decide any disputed facts regarding competency with an instruction to disregard the witness&apos; testimony if they find the witness incompetent.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76569a5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference><?page no="12"?>] The court may allow the jury to decide even in the unusual situation where the disputed facts involve more than the capacity of a witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7656c16074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] Absent manifest abuse of discretion, the appellate court will uphold the trial court&apos;s decision.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7656c16174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7655aff074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-601" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I9174b34074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-601</cite.query>: <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“Except as otherwise provided in this chapter, every person is competent to be a witness.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1847001304" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I9175016174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Adams v. Barrett, 3 Ga. 277, 1847 WL 1340 (1847)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1926105642" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I9175016574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Goodson v. State, 162 Ga. 178, 132 S.E. 899 (1926)</cite.query><?page no="11"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7655d70074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Black&apos;s Law Dictionary (9th ed.).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7655d70174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-601" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I91759da074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-601</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7655fe1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-1-104" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I917612d074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-1-104</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7655fe1174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1978109888" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I917660f274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Redfield v. State, 240 Ga. 460, 241 S.E.2d 217 (1978)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1978109958" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I917660f574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Smith v. State, 144 Ga. App. 579, 241 S.E.2d 465 (1978)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="2012410888" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I917660f874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Austin v. State, 286 Ga. App. 149, 648 S.E.2d 414 (2007)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7656252074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1951104890" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9176fd3274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Schamroth v. State, 84 Ga. App. 580, 66 S.E.2d 413 (1951)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1973128007" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9176fd3574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Overton v. State, 230 Ga. 830, 199 S.E.2d 205 (1973)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76564c3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1965125773" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9177726274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Dawn Memorial Park v. DeKalb County, 111 Ga. App. 429, 142 S.E.2d 72 (1965)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76564c3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1985132798" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9177c08274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sprayberry v. State, 174 Ga. App. 574, 330 S.E.2d 731 (1985)</cite.query>, the court allowed counsel to question child victims in a competency examination conducted outside the presence of the jury.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76564c3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1985102751" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I917835b274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Middlebrooks v. State, 253 Ga. 707, 324 S.E.2d 192 (1985)</cite.query>, the Georgia Supreme Court upheld the trial court&apos;s refusal to allow defendant&apos;s counsel to question a child witness during a competency examination.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7656734074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1987076784" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I9179201274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Kentucky v. Stincer, 482 U.S. 730, 107 S. Ct. 2658, 96 L. Ed. 2d 631, 22 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 1164 (1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76569a5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="2014964395" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I9179e36274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Luther v. Luther, 289 Ga. App. 428, 657 S.E.2d 574 (2008)</cite.query>, the Court of Appeals upheld the trial court&apos;s ruling of incompetency when the witness&apos; physician testified that she had impaired mental capacity.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76569a5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1902010504" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I917a589274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Dowdy v. Watson, 115 Ga. 42, 41 S.E. 266 (1902)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1926105642" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I917a589574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Goodson v. State, 162 Ga. 178, 132 S.E. 899 (1926)</cite.query><?page no="12"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7656c16074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1938106489" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I917acdc274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Scott v. State, 57 Ga. App. 489, 195 S.E. 923 (1938)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7656c16174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1974127546" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I917b1be274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Geter v. State, 231 Ga. 615, 203 S.E.2d 195 (1974)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018080" w-serial-number="1980109637" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I917b1be574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hawkins v. Hawkins, 245 Ga. 284, 264 S.E.2d 218 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
